182. Ennosiyaeum. Ἐννοσίγαιος properly Ἐνοσίγαιος, a name of Nep- tune, from ἒνόθω “to move,” and γαὶα, so also Ἐνοα-ίχθων in Homer and ὅ mum-323 ‘75⁶5 (Pindar). These epithets seem to have been given to Nep- tune from the circumstance, that when earthquakes occur the sea is greatly agitated. Gellius assi gns another explanation, namely, that earthquakes may have been thought by the ancients to be occasioned by the agita- tion of waters in the depths of the earth. Perhaps, as Neptune was the personified symbol of all waters, allusion may be made by this name to the deluge of Ogyges, which broke down the mountains which hemmed in the inland sea formerly covering Thessaly, and formed a passage through the vale of Tempe.
